LIBER QUARTUS. SUMMAR.Y OF THE CONTENTS.

AFTER some preliminary remarks on the history of Roman civiliza· tion (cap. 1—3), Cicero introduces the Disputation on the thesis, Non omni animi perturbacione sapiens potest vacare. It consists of three parts :-1. Classification and definition of the four perturbationes and their species, according to the Stoical system (cap. 6—14). 2. Refu- tation of the thesis itself, with an especial reference to the doctrine of the Peripatetics, respecting the necessity and utility of the pas- sions (cap. 15—26). 3. statement of the means to be employed for resistiug them (cap. 27- 38).
